<br>
Function: to give mercenaries access to the same reasonable and noticeable figures of damage increase that TW and BZK offer their users.<br>
<br>
Points cost: 10 if Mythic really loves us, for a Merc RSPs are like gold: we just dont GET ANY!<br>
Pre-req: You must be a merc <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
Timer: 7 minutes<br>
Duration: 20 seconds<br>
<br>
Will reward: mercenaries with fast weapons, double-procced weapons, Mastey of Pain RA, high Dual Wield spec, Duellists Reflexes RA, all the things we know we're supposed to have. Also benefits the use of Dirty Tricks and makes us better at our job - whether it's caster-killing, Preventing Flight or Dirty Tricking people. Oh, and Mythic says we're good at popping PB- that's practically the class description now, and this RA would make us better at that as well.<br>
<br>
Problem: At this stage the mercenary seems to be one of the weakest classes in the game, on the battlefield. No, no, hear me out <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  - With the exception of the pre-1.62 'Zerker, and the Savage which has superceeded this old enemy and literally massacres casters, the Light Tank is probably the least fortunate army assett due to the problems associated with performing his job- killing casters or healers fast enough. It's well known that the tank has the hardest job on the entire battlefield (CHARGE THOSE CANNONS, MAJOR, AND I'LL SEE YOU IN HELL!) with the possible exception of the Cleric, who I've always felt sorry for, but most of them seem to be nice guys <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
The ability to deal lots damage over time is nice for PvE, and with the positional and reactive style changes the mercenary might actually be a formidable fighting force, particularly one with high parry. But if the merc is meant to be the guy killing the MOC'd PBAoE Spiritmaster(s) who is guarded by a Warrior, he's got three other things coming and none of them are good. It makes killing a berzerker solo look easy. Damage-over time won't help us kill casters or healers in the same time-frame of our heavier comrades: the 3-shot polearmsman who can drop somebody in 8 seconds after the initial 1/3 frontload or even the 'defensive' Slam Paladin who has the ability to charge this 'living minefield' and simple stun him/them for a whole 9 seconds. Tanks know painfully, better than anyone else, that it's CC and big single hits (read the Emain death spam and you'll see a lot of Wizards and not a lot of Mercenaries) that win wars.<br>
<br>
Proposal: I've not yet witnessed the working effects of the new TW, but it sounds pretty similar to Berzerk. A damage increase of probably 40-50% of what the BM or 'Zerk is already hitting for, an ability that will work moderately against &quot;tanks&quot; but is particularly suited to lower AF targets.<br>
<br>
This RA, when active, would work differently, but to similar effect. Every time the Mercenary procs a DW swing (this should be approximately 62.5% of the time, if he's got 50DW) he will swing his mainhand two times, as well as his offhand once. Damage- adds such as Damage-Chants and Earthern Buffs will be taken into account, and the chance to critical hit, proc a weapon (Alchemy), proc Dirty Tricks (if active) or proc Prevent Flight (which costs 14 points) are likewise. <br>
<br>
Style bonuses from performing a combat style will apply only to the first mainhand swing, not the second. The second mainhand swing will retain no 'to-hit bonus' (just like the offhand). Swing speeds for the round will be averaged between the THREE weapons connecting, so 'The Haste Effect' will not be as beneficial when using a slow/fast combination of weapons. These are to prevent this resembling another Left Axe problem where the style bonuses were 2x too big on swings, and the &quot;haste effect&quot; was exploited due to the 100% DW rate. Instead, this ability should resemble a 'upgraded' version of the &quot;Dual Wield&quot; combat system we are already familiar with.<br>
<br>
